'''Coal India Limited''' ('''CIL''') ({{BSE|533278}}, {{NSE|COALINDIA}}) is an Indian [[Government-owned corporation|state-controlled]] [[coal mining]] company headquartered in [[Kolkata, West Bengal]], India and the world's largest coal miner with revenue exceeding {{INR}}602.45 billion (FY2010-11).<ref>{{cite web|last=Katakey |first=Rakteem |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-05-13/world-s-largest-coal-producer-plans-555-million-savings-by-using-machines.html |title=World's Largest Coal Producer Plans $555 Million Savings by Using Machines |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2010-05-13 |accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=September 04, 2009 12:00AM |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/business/story/0,28124,26022838-5005200,00.html |title=Rio, Hancock planning to sell mine stakes to Coal India &#124; The Australian |publisher=Theaustralian.news.com.au |date=2009-09-04 |accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref> It was formerly owned entirely by the [[Government of India|Union Government of India]], under the administrative control of the [[Ministry of Coal (India)|Ministry of Coal]]. It is involved in  [[coal mining]] and production industry. In April 2011, CIL was conferred the [[Navratna#Maharatna_status|Maharatna]] status by the [[Government of India|Union Government of India]] <ref>[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/indl-goods-/-svs/metals-mining/coal-india-gets-maharatna-tag/articleshow/7943638.cms Coal India gets Maharatna tag - Economic Times Article]</ref> and ranked as one of India's most valuable company by [[market value]]. 

In 2010, CIL's [[initial public offering]] (IPO) got subscribed 15.28 times, collecting a record over {{INR}}2.4 trillion<U+2014>the highest IPO subscription so far.<ref name="CIL">{{cite web|title= Retail investors join the Coal India party|url= http://business.rediff.com/report/2010/oct/22/retail-investors-join-the-coal-india-party.htm|publisher=business.rediff.com|accessdate=25 Oct 2010}}</ref> On the first day of its listing on the [[Sensex]], its stock closed 40% higher than IPO price.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sinha|first=Varun|title=Sensex hits 52-week high on global cues, Coal India listing|url=http://profit.ndtv.com/news/show/sensex-hits-52-week-high-on-global-cues-coal-india-listing-118306|accessdate=4 November 2010|newspaper=[[NDTV]]|date=4 November 2010}}</ref> It is India's largest ever public offer from Coal India Ltd. to raise up to {{INRConvert|15000|c}}.<ref>[http://www.indianstockmarketnews.info/2010/08/biggest-ipos-10-largest-ipos-of-all.html CIL in Fortune India list]</ref> It is currently 90% owned by the Government of India with the remaining 10% owned by the public. 

==History==
Coal India Limited was formed in 1973 as Coal Mines Authority Limited. In 1975 it was changed to Coal India Limited as a [[holding company]] with five [[Subsidiary|subsidiaries]]:
*[[Bharat Coking Coal|Bharat Coking Coal Limited]] (BCCL)(Dhanbad, Jharkhand)
*[[Central Coalfields Limited]] (CCL)(Ranchi, Jharkhand)
*[[Western Coalfields Limited]] (WCL)(Nagpur region)
*[[Eastern Coalfields Limited]] (ECL)(Sanctoria, Asansol, West Bengal) 
*[[Central Mine Planning and Design Institute Limited]] (CMPDIL)(Ranchi, Jharkhand)

In 1985 two more subsidiaries were added:
*[[South Eastern Coalfields Limited]] (SECL)(Bilaspur) 
*[[Northern Coalfields Limited]], Singrauli (NCL,Singrauli)

In 1992 one more subsidiary added:
*[[Mahanadi Coalfields Limited]] (MCL) (Sambalpur)

One International Subsidiary
*[[Coal India Africana Limitada]] (CIAL) (Mozambique)

Two indirect subsidiaries (held through our subsidiary, Mahanadi Coalfields Limited)
*MJSJ Coal Limited
*MNH Shakti Limited

The Indian Institute of Coal Management (IICM) at Ranchi operates under Coal India Limited and imparts multi disciplinary management development programs executives.

In April 2012,  S Narsing Rao is expected to take over as the Coal India Chief.[http://www.brightwire.com/company/53033-coal-india-ltd] <ref>{{cite web|title=S Narsing Roa to take over as Coal India Chief|url=http://www.brightwire.com/news/200867-rao-to-be-officially-appointed-as-chief-of-coal-india-next-week|publisher=BrightWire}}</ref>

==Reviving of abandoned mines==
Coal India Ltd (CIL), will extract coal from 18 abandoned underground mines owned by three of its subsidiaries in partnership with private players. Underground mining would be revived in 6 abandoned mines of Eastern Coalfields, 8 mines of Bharat Coking Coal, and 4 mines of Central Coalfields. These 18 mines have an approximate reserve of 1.647 billion tons of coal.<ref>[http://in.news.yahoo.com/43/20080813/836/tbs-coal-india-to-restart-excavation-in.html Coal India to restart excavation in 18 abandoned mines]{{dead link|date=October 2010}}</ref>

CIL contributes around 85% of coal production in India. It is the largest company in the world in terms of coal production. It
employs nearly 397,000 person and is the largest corporate employer in the country. It is one of the largest companies in the country, with turnover being around {{INR}}386.31 billion in 2007-08. It is one of the largest tax payer (Corporate Tax  {{INRConvert|35.75|b}}) in 2007-08 and has paid Dividend of {{INRConvert|17.054|b}} to the Govt. of India in 2007-08.

